"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386277","Department of Health","false","2015-07-02","<p>The Department currently has no plans to revise the Certificate of Vision Impairment. However, following discussions with the Royal National Institute of Blind People, Blind Veterans UK, NHS England, NHS optometry leads and the Health and Social Care Information Centre other options for identifying visually impaired veterans are being explored.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-07-02T14:09:28.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386277/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386277/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386277/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-29","Veterans: Visual Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will introduce an option for people to identify themselves as a veteran on the Certificate of Vision Impairment.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","4651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386278","Department of Health","false","2015-07-07","<p>National statistics are published on the proportion of patients who begin first treatment within 62 days from urgent referral for suspected cancer. No equivalent statistics are published for patients who start treatment within 62 days of diagnosis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The data are available for major cancer groups. NHS England advises that releasing data at the more detailed cancer site levels would be reliant on detailed clinical coding and would risk disclosing patient identities.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-07-07T13:10:08.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386278/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386278/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386278/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-29","Pancreatic Cancer: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the proportion of newly-diagnosed pancreatic cancer patients who start treatment within 62 days of diagnosis; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","4533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386279","Department of Health","false","2015-07-07","<p>No such estimate has been made. These are matters for the trusts concerned.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-07-07T15:50:32.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386279/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386279/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386279/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-29","Health Professions: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the likely spend on agency (a) doctors and (b) nurses by (i) North Middlesex University NHS Trust and (ii) Royal Free London NHS Trust in each financial year up to 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","4675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386280","Department of Health","false","2015-07-07","<p>Data on waiting times to see a general practitioner are not collected centrally.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-07-07T13:04:05.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386280/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386280/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386280/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-29","General Practitioners: Enfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients in the Enfield Clinical Commissioning Group had to wait longer than 48 hours for a GP appointment in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","4674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386281","Department of Health","false","2015-07-07","<p>The Health Working Group Report on Child Sexual Exploitation made 13 recommendations, some of which were directed to our arm‘s length bodies and other national organisations. We set out the actions being taken in our response to the recommendations in May 2014. Some of those actions are continuing and others are completed. An update on progress will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-07-07T13:32:52.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386281/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386281/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386281/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-29","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress his Department has made on implementing its response to the independent health working group report on child sexual exploitation published in May 2014.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","4616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386282","Department of Health","false","2015-07-07","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The hon. Member may wish to contact North Middlesex University Hospitals NHS Trust directly for further information.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>I have written to Dominic Dodd, Chair of the Royal Free London NHS Foundation Trust, informing him of the hon. Member’s enquiry. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following the Francis report many trusts increased their spend on temporary staffing to meet safe staffing levels. The Department expects trusts to have a strong grip on their finances, and manage their contract and agency staffing spend (including use of locums) responsibly through effective and efficient workforce planning and management and to minimise temporary staffing costs in future years.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-07-07T15:43:20.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386282/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386282/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386282/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-29","Health Professions: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much was spent on agency (a) doctors and (b) nurses by (i) North Middlesex University NHS Trust and (ii) Royal Free London NHS Trust in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","4683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386283","Department of Health","false","2015-07-07","<p>The Urgent and Emergency Care Review identified a number of factors that impact on accident and emergency (A&amp;E) attendances which can include local access to general practitioners (GPs).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are expanding access to GPs in the evenings and at the weekend. Through the Prime Minister’s Challenge Fund, 18 million people will benefit from improved access, including at evenings and weekends by March 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>According to the latest GP Patient Survey results, published on 2 July 2015, 85.2% of patients were able to get an appointment with a GP or nurse at their surgery. 91.8% of those were able to get an appointment convenient to them. Of the 10.9% who reported that they could not get an appointment and the 8.2% who could not get an appointment that was convenient, 9.9% went to A&amp;E or a walk-in centre.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-07-07T13:22:48.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386283/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386283/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386283/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-29","General Practitioners: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of a link between access to GPs and attendances at accident and emergency departments.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","4686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386284","Department of Health","false","2015-07-02","<p>We have made no such assessment. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is responsible for providing guidance to the National Health Service on the clinical and cost effectiveness of selected drugs and indications through its technology appraisal programme. NICE has published several pieces of technology appraisal guidance covering a number of different technologies for use in the treatment of adults and children with asthma. Further information is available on NICE’s website at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/conditions-and-diseases/respiratory-conditions/asthma" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/guidance/conditions-and-diseases/respiratory-conditions/asthma</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-07-02T12:15:21.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386284/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386284/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386284/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-29","Asthma: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the cost effectiveness of prescribing medicines for asthma patients; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","4661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386285","Department of Health","false","2015-07-02","<p>The full business case for the ‘Teaching, Trauma and Tertiary care’ (‘3Ts’) redevelopment at the Royal Sussex County Hospital has been submitted to the NHS Trust Development Authority for approval. The business case has also been shared with the Department and HM Treasury.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-07-02T13:26:42.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386285/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386285/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386285/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-29","Royal Sussex County Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the full business case for the teaching, trauma and tertiary care at the Royal Sussex County Hospital in Brighton has been submitted to (a) the NHS Trust Development Authority, (b) his Department and (c) HM Treasury.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","4634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386286","Home Office","false","2015-07-09","<p>Local management information shows that on 1 June 2010, there were a total of 31 Entry Clearance Officers employed in Mumbai. 18 of these staff were employed on a long-term basis and 13 were employed as seasonal relief to process increased volumes of applications in the peak period for Western Indian visa applications to the UK. On 1 June 2015 local management information shows that there were a total of 24 Entry Clearance Officers employed in Mumbai. 15 of these staff were employed on a long-term basis and 9 were employed as seasonal relief to process increased volumes of applications in the peak period for Western Indian visa applications to the UK.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-07-09T15:13:58.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386286/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386286/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386286/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Entry Clearances: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many entry clearance officers were employed by her Department in Mumbai on 1 June (a) 2010 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386287","Home Office","false","2015-07-09","<p>The Home Department currently holds two contracts with Teleperformance Ltd.</p><p>The Next Generation Outsourced Visa Services contract, which has a total value of £33.3 million exc. VAT per annum for a maximum of 9 years and a minimum of 5 years. This contract is for the provision of services (to supplement the Home Department’s own in-house resources and services) for the support and delivery of the Home Department’s visa application services in 79 countries across Africa and Europe.</p><p>The Contact Centre Services contract for Her Majesty’s Passport Office, which has a total value of £10 million exc. VAT per annum for a maximum of 5 years and a minimum of 3 years. This contract is for the provision of contact centre services for phone and e-mail contacts from UK and International passport customers.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-07-09T13:55:48.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386287/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386287/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386287/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Home Office: Teleperformance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the total value is of contracts currently held with her Department by Teleperformance Ltd; and what each such contract relates to.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386288","Home Office","false","2015-07-03","<p>The publication of crime statistics is the responsibility of the Office for National Statistics (ONS). Latest published figures (from Crime in England and Wales, year ending December 2014) show that according to the independent Crime Survey for England and Wales violence is 23% lower than it was in 2010. This is supported by National Health Service data on hospital admissions for assault, which also indicates violence is falling.</p><p>The ONS note that the recent changes in the level of violent crime recorded by the police relates to action taken by police forces, including the Metropolitan Police, to improve their compliance with the National Crime Recording Standard. This renewed focus on the accuracy of crime recording by the police is likely to have resulted in the increase in the number of offences recorded. However, we closely monitor trends in violent crime, and in the last Parliament we took action to strengthen legislation on knives to create new offences and introduce new sentences.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-07-03T13:23:55.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386288/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386288/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386288/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Crimes of Violence: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of reasons for changes in the level of violent crime against the person in (a) Enfield and (b) London in the year to May 2015; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","4682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386289","Home Office","false","2015-07-09","<p>Thefollowing table shows the latest published number of nationals of (i) Syria, (ii) Eritrea, (iii) Afghanistan, (iv) Somalia, (v) Nigeria, (vi) Palestine, (vii) Iraq and (viii) Libya in each of the last five years that have (a) applied for and (b) been granted asylum or an alternative form of protection in the UK, based on initial decisions for main applicants.</p><p>The figures provided in the table are published by the Home Office in the Immigration Statistics release, in Table as_01.</p><p>The Home Office publishes quarterly and annual statistics on asylum applications and initial decisions within the Immigration Statistics release. A copy of the latest release, Immigration Statistics January – March 2015 is available from https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release and the Library of the House.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-07-09T15:17:50.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386289/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386289/answer","PQ 4645 Table(1).xlsx","Asylum applications published figures","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386289/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386289/answer/previousversion/10708","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have (a) applied for and (b) been granted asylum from (i) Syria, (ii) Eritrea, (iii) Afghanistan, (iv) Somalia, (v) Nigeria, (vi) Palestine, (vii) Iraq and (viii) Libya in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","4645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386290","Attorney General","false","2015-07-06","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) maintains a central record of the number of defendants whose prosecution was completed and where the principal offence at finalisation is categorised as a sexual offence.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>During each of the last ten years the number of defendants prosecuted, in (a) North Wales and (b) England &amp; Wales, whose principal offence was identified as a sexual offence, is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>North Wales</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>England &amp; Wales</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2005-2006</strong></p></td><td><p>113</p></td><td><p>11,481</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2006-2007</strong></p></td><td><p>118</p></td><td><p>11,129</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2007-2008</strong></p></td><td><p>106</p></td><td><p>11,099</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2008-2009</strong></p></td><td><p>125</p></td><td><p>10,878</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009-2010</strong></p></td><td><p>99</p></td><td><p>11,174</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010-2011</strong></p></td><td><p>162</p></td><td><p>12,472</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011-2012</strong></p></td><td><p>125</p></td><td><p>11,735</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012-2013</strong></p></td><td><p>124</p></td><td><p>11,002</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013-2014</strong></p></td><td><p>145</p></td><td><p>12,040</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014-2015</strong></p></td><td><p>225</p></td><td><p>13,778</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Data Source: CPS Case Management Information System</p></td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to disaggregate figures to show separately the volume and outcome of proceedings for individual offences within the Sexual Offences Category. A single defendant may be charged with more than one offence.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-07-06T13:35:26.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386290/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386290/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386290/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-06-29","Sexual Offences: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many sexual offences leading to prosecution there have been in (a) North Wales and (b) the UK in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","4589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386291","Home Office","false","2015-07-07","<p>Sue Langley, OBE and Alan Brown are the non-executive members of the Home Office Board.</p><p>Sue Langley is currently the CEO of the Government's UK Financial Services Investment Organisation. She is a Non Executive Director for UKAR (Northern Rock Asset Management and Bradford and Bingley) and Chairman of the Remuneration Committee.</p><p>Previously she was Director of Market Development and a member of the Executive Team for Lloyd's of London, a Director of Lloyd’s Asia and Chairman of Lloyd’s Japan. Prior to this Sue was Chief Operating Officer and a member of the executive team for the Hiscox Group, holding various board positions. She joined Hiscox from PriceWaterhouseCoopers where she was a Principal Consultant and worked with a range of FTSE 100 companies. Sue is a representative on the Women's Business Council. She is a Vice President of the Insurance Institute of London.</p><p>Alan Brown is currently Chief Executive Officer at ASCO – an international oilfield support services company and a global provider of outsourced logistics services to the oil and gas industry. He is a non- executive director of Intertek, the FTSE 100-listed testing inspection and certification business.</p><p>Previously, Alan was Chief Executive Officer of Rentokil Initial plc for five years until October 2013. Alan spent 25 years at Unilever plc, in various roles in the UK and Europe and then CEO of Unilever’s operations in Taiwan and then China. Following this, Alan returned to the UK as Chief Financial Officer at Imperial Chemical Industries plc.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-07-07T15:54:22.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386291/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386291/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386291/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Home Office: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the (a) names and (b) previous occupations are of the non-executive member of the Home Office Board.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386292","Home Office","false","2015-07-03","<p>A key element of the established process for the approval of less lethal weapons, including water cannon, is an assessment by the Scientific Advisory Committee on the Medical Implications of Less-Lethal weapons. This has only recently been received. There are a number of scientific, medical, operational and ethical issues which need careful consideration before a decision will be made.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-07-03T13:27:15.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386292/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386292/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386292/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Riot Control Weapons: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has made a decision on the application of the Mayor of London for the use of water cannon in London.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386293","Home Office","false","2015-07-07","<p>Section 42 of the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 (RIPA) provides that intrusive surveillance by the intelligence agencies can only be carried out under the authority of a warrant signed by a Secretary of State. Under section 42(2), RIPA also allows the Secretary of State to make a combined authorisation of intrusive surveillance and interference with property (under the Intelligence Services Act 1994).</p><p>The exercise of these powers is subject to scrutiny by the Intelligence Services Commissioner and is covered in his Annual Reports, which include statistics for the number of warrants signed by Secretaries of State. These reports, including the most recent one published on 25 June 2015, can be found at: www.intelligencecommissioner.com.</p><p>For reasons of national security, it has been the practice of successive governments not to publish more detailed breakdowns of the number of warrants authorised under section 42 of RIPA.</p><p>As the Right Honourable Member will be aware, directed surveillance authorisations, and intrusive surveillance authorisations for agencies other than the intelligence agencies, are not issued by the Secretary of State.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-07-07T16:00:13.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386293/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386293/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386293/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many surveillance warrants she signed (a) between 2010 and 2015 and (b) since 7 May 2015.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386294","Home Office","false","2015-07-03","<p>I regularly receive representations on a variety of matters relating to police pensions. This is a broad subject with a range of interested parties.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-07-03T13:24:18.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386294/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386294/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386294/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Police: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent representations she has received on police pensions.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386295","Home Office","false","2015-07-09","<p>The number of officials working in the Home Office is recorded at the end of each month; therefore the numbers of officials provided in tables 1 and 2 is as on 31 December in 2009 and 2014.</p><p> </p><p>It is important to note as context that Machinery of Government changes have taken place during this period, including 4,639 FTE officials transferring from HMRC to join the Home Office on 1st April 2010 to undertake functions previously carried out by HMRC. Excluding these machinery changes, the Home Office reduced the number of staff by almost 2000 officials by 2014 compared to 2010.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-07-09T14:01:41.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386295/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386295/answer","PQ4696 No of HO Officials 1st Jan 2015 table 1 and table 2(1).xlsx","The number of officials working in the Home Dept.","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386295/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Home Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many officials were employed in her Department on 1 January (a) 2010 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386296","Home Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>As at 31 May 2015, 3,323 National Crime Agency officers had previously worked for the Serious Organised Crime Agency.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-07-06T13:51:32.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386296/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386296/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386296/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","National Crime Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff of the National Crime Agency previously worked for the Serious Organised Crime Agency.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386297","Home Office","false","2015-07-09","<p>Until 31st March 2015, no appeal outcomes have been recorded on appeals related to in-country settlement cases where the application was refused between 1st January 2015 and 31st March 2015.</p><p>Between 1st January and 31st March 2015, 228 appeals were allowed at the First-tier Tribunal which related to an earlier in-country settlement application.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-07-09T15:12:10.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386297/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386297/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386297/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Visas: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many appeals have been granted following refusal of the granting of a settlement visa since 1 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386298","Home Office","false","2015-07-07","<p>Each Department reports its sick leave to Cabinet Office as part of a twelve month rolling year figure; this allows for comparisons to be made across the civil service, taking into account both the size and employee profile of each Department.</p><p>In 2014 176,665 working days were lost due to sick absence, an average working days lost of 6.88 per staff year. The Department was amongst the best across government when compared to other 'large' and 'very large' Departments and the civil service average was 7.4 for the same period.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-07-07T15:53:30.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386298/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386298/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386298/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Home Office: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many days of sick leave employees in her Department took in 2014.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386299","Home Office","false","2015-07-07","<p>The names and salaries of officials of director general rank are published in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts. These are available for the 2013/14 financial year at: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/321446/ARA_web_enabled_18_June.pdf</p><p>I am unable to disclose financial data for 2014/15 until the Home Office’s 2014/15 Annual Report and Accounts are published. These will be published on www.gov.uk in due course.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-07-07T15:53:50.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386299/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386299/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386299/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-29","Home Office: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the (a) names and (b) salaries are of officials of director general rank in her Department.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386300","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-06","<p>The UK Government alone has committed £33 million to the Earthquake response in Nepal. This is part of a wider global response to this disaster which currently stands at £371 million in pledged humanitarian support. Assistance from the UK Government will reach over 200,000 people with shelter; 80,000 with cash transfers in compliment to the Government of Nepal’s assistance; over 30,000 people with safe water, and improved hygiene and sanitation; 30,000 people with blankets, cooking sets, and other essential day-to-day household items; 15,000 women and girls with gender and protection initiatives; and over 3,000 people with rehabilitation services. We are also providing support to humanitarian logistics through aircraft and trucking, whilst ensuring information is central to the response through support to beneficiary feedback mechanisms and needs assessments.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>DFID is working closely with trusted UN and NGO partners and experts in the humanitarian field to ensure that the supplies distributed are high quality. Emergency shelter supplies provided to our partners conform to international SPHERE and ISO standards for quality, and technical guidance from the Shelter Cluster also reflects these standards.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-07-06T16:08:45.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386300/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386300/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386300/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-29","Nepal: Disaster Relief","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what reports she has received on the quality and quantity of aid (a) promised and (b) delivered to Nepal following the earthquakes of 25 April and 12 May 2015.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","4561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386301","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-06","<p>We are deeply concerned for the safety of civilians and humanitarian staff present in Kobane following recent reports of an ISIL incursion into the city. The Syrian Observatory for Human Rights reported that between 145 and 200 civilians were killed in the ISIL attack, and many more were wounded. We are watching the latest developments closely and continue to call on all sides of the conflict to respect International Humanitarian Law and protect civilians.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-07-06T16:09:46.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386301/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386301/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386301/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-29","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the humanitarian situation in Kobane following the recent attack by ISIL.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","4670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386302","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-02","<p>The Ministry of Justice have kept the Bribery Act Guidance under review since it was published in 2011. There are no plans to revise or replace the existing guidance.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-07-02T12:25:26.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386302/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386302/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386302/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-29","Bribery Act 2010","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to make changes to his Department's guidance on the Bribery Act 2010 and facilitation payments and hospitality.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","4539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386303","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-02","<p>From 1 May 2015 Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) have been delivering a Through the Gate (TTG) resettlement service to the vast majority of offenders, so that they benefit from continuity of support from custody to the community. Resettlement services delivered to offenders include help with finding or retaining employment and accommodation, and advice on finance and debt. CRCs are delivering TTG services to both National Probation Service (NPS) and CRC managed offenders. The NPS can also commission additional rehabilitation services from CRCs above mandated TTG services where they believe it will help reduce reoffending.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-02T14:10:30.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386303/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386303/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386303/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-29","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps are taken by the National Probation Service to ensure that prison leavers can access benefits and food when they leave prison.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","4631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386304","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-09","<p>For the period February 2014 to January 2015 the following volumes were purchased</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Meat</p></td><td><p>Total (Kg)</p></td><td><p>Proportion from UK</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(a) Lamb</p></td><td><p>236,838</p></td><td><p>22%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(b) Beef</p></td><td><p>753,258</p></td><td><p>24%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(c) Pork</p></td><td><p>653,938</p></td><td><p>51%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(d) Poultry</p></td><td><p>2,570,750</p></td><td><p>51%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-09T12:58:22.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386304/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386304/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386304/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-29","Prisons: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much (a) lamb, (b) beef, (c) pork and (d) poultry meat is purchased annually for consumption in prisons; and what proportion of each type of meat is British.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","4564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386305","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-07","<p>We have taken decisive action to reduce reoffending. For the first time in recent history those sentenced to less than 12 months in custody receive support on release. We have also opened up the delivery of rehabilitation services to a diverse range of providers, including private, voluntary and third sector organisations, who will only be paid in full if they are successful in reducing reoffending and helping offenders turn their backs on crime.</p><p> </p><p>These organisations are now providing ‘Through the Gate’ resettlement services to virtually all those in custody, including help with finding or retaining employment and accommodation, and advice on finance and debt. Under ‘Through the Gate’ the vast majority of prisoners will benefit from a universal resettlement service and continuity of provision from custody to the community.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-07T14:50:33.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386305/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386305/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-29","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to reduce reoffending.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","4549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386306","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-02","<p>Modernisation funding was allocated to the Ministry of Justice by HM Treasury in 2014/15 to bring about sustainable reductions in resource requirements across the Ministry. Some of this funding was made available for voluntary redundancies in Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs). Of this, £16.4m was spent on voluntary exit packages in 2014/15 and the remainder was allocated to CRCs on a pro-rata basis, based on their size and estimated future staffing requirements.</p><p> </p><p>Each Community Rehabilitation Company (CRC) is managed by a Contract Management Team (CMT), headed by a Senior Contract Manager and comprising staff with commercial, contract management and operational expertise to ensure a multi-disciplinary approach. The size of teams reflects the size of the contract being managed. While it is for CRC owners to implement and oversee redundancy schemes, CMTs are ensuring that CRC owners adhere to their contractual obligations in this area. CMTs are able to draw upon commercial, financial and legal expertise from within the wider Ministry in delivering this role.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","4574","2015-07-02T13:42:52.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386306/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386306/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-29","Community Rehabilitation Companies: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 9 June 2015 to Question 1763, what the total cash value was of the Modernisation Fund; and how much of that fund was taken and distributed to Community Rehabilitation Companies for enhanced redundancy schemes following the privatisation of probation services.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","4573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386307","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-02","<p>Modernisation funding was allocated to the Ministry of Justice by HM Treasury in 2014/15 to bring about sustainable reductions in resource requirements across the Ministry. Some of this funding was made available for voluntary redundancies in Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs). Of this, £16.4m was spent on voluntary exit packages in 2014/15 and the remainder was allocated to CRCs on a pro-rata basis, based on their size and estimated future staffing requirements.</p><p> </p><p>Each Community Rehabilitation Company (CRC) is managed by a Contract Management Team (CMT), headed by a Senior Contract Manager and comprising staff with commercial, contract management and operational expertise to ensure a multi-disciplinary approach. The size of teams reflects the size of the contract being managed. While it is for CRC owners to implement and oversee redundancy schemes, CMTs are ensuring that CRC owners adhere to their contractual obligations in this area. CMTs are able to draw upon commercial, financial and legal expertise from within the wider Ministry in delivering this role.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","4573","2015-07-02T13:42:52.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386307/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386307/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386307/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-29","Community Rehabilitation Companies: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 9 June 2015 to Question 1761, how many staff of what grade are embedded in each Community Rehabilitation Company; and what training such staff have received for overseeing enhanced redundancy schemes.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","4574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386308","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-07","<p>The evaluation of the pilot of recorded pre-trial cross-examination (Section 28 of the Youth Justice and Criminal Evidence Act 1999) will be completed in due course.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-07-07T14:45:02.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386308/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386308/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-29","Youth Justice and Criminal Evidence Act 1999","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he plans to complete the evaluation of the pilots of section 28 of the Youth Justice and Criminal Evidence Act 1999.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","4545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386309","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-07","<p>From 1<sup>st</sup> January to 6<sup>th</sup> May (inclusive), 42 salaried and 105 fee-paid judges were appointed. From 7<sup>th</sup> May to 30<sup>th</sup> June (inclusive), 19 salaried and 76 fee-paid judges were appointed.</p><p>All salaried judicial appointments are announced on the Judiciary Website. This can be found at: <a title="https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/announcement-type/appointments-and-retirements/" href="https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/announcement-type/appointments-and-retirements/" target="_blank">https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/announcement-type/appointments-and-retirements/</a></p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-07-07T15:07:15.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386309/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386309/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386309/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-29","Judges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many judges have been appointed since (a) 1 January and (b) 7 May 2015.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","4703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386310","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>My management board is made up of four executive members and one non-executive member. Of the four executive members, three are male and one is female. The one non-executive member is female. The current members are:</p><p>Sir Jonathan Stephens, Chair, Permanent Secretary;</p><p>Mark Larmour, Director;</p><p>Colin Perry, Director;</p><p>Dawn Johnson, Non-Executive Director;</p><p>Jo Gordon, Deputy Director.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-07-06T14:27:32.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386310/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386310/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386310/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-29","Northern Ireland Office: Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, who the members of the management board of her Department are; and how many of those members are women.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","4626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386311","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>The total cost of the Hallett Review was £509,417. Expenditure is broken down as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Spend (£s)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Chair</p></td><td><p>69,458</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Legal and specialist</p></td><td><p>265,486</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Staff</p></td><td><p>40,298</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Travel and accommodation</p></td><td><p>9,504</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>IT and comms.</p></td><td><p>45,602</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Admin.</p></td><td><p>1,941</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Publication</p></td><td><p>77,128</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>509,417</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-07-06T14:32:28.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386311/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386311/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386311/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-29","Administrative Scheme for the "On the Runs" Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the total cost under each cost heading was of the Hallett Review into On The Runs.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","4688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386312","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>I have had no discussions with the Chancellor about the Horse Race Betting Levy because Northern Ireland has its own devolved Horse Racing Fund. This is administered by the Department of Agriculture and Rural Development to assist the maintenance and development of horse racing in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-07-06T14:33:52.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386312/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386312/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386312/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-29","Horse Racing: Betting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, with reference to paragraph 2.152 of Budget 2015, HC1093, what discussions she has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the extension of the Horserace Betting Right to Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for George Kerevan","East Lothian","George Kerevan","4610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386313","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>Information relating to internal discussions and advice is not normally disclosed.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-06T11:54:23.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386313/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386313/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386313/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-29","SG First Minister: Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether any (a) Minister and (b) Scotland Office Special Advisers were sent responses to Freedom of Information requests concerning the memo written by a Scotland Office civil servant on 6 March 2015 containing an account of the meeting between the Scottish First Minister and the French Ambassador before they were sent to the inquirers.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","4656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386314","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-06","<p>Following the leak of a Scotland Office memorandum that formed the basis of a story in the Daily Telegraph on 3 April, which was when I first became aware of the leak, the Cabinet Secretary instigated a Cabinet Office-led inquiry to establish how the memo to which the honourable Member refers came to be written and how it got into the public domain. The findings of the inquiry were published on the 22 May 2015 and are available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/scotland-office-memorandum-leak-cabinet-office-inquiry-statement" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/scotland-office-memorandum-leak-cabinet-office-inquiry-statement</a>. These findings specifically refer to the role of the then Special Advisor and the former Secretary of State for Scotland. These findings also make clear that no one else had any involvement in the leaking of the memo.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","4654 ; 4655 ; 4658","2015-07-06T11:59:44.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386314/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386314/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/386314/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-29","SG First Minister: Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, when he first became aware of the memorandum written by a Scotland Office civil servant on 6 March 2015, containing an account of the meeting between the Scottish First Minister and the French Ambassador.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","4657"
